{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos1108.erdos_1108.parts.ii https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos1108.erdos_1108.parts.ii.","id":"vf_54d3d03923222b0a","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #1108: declared status 'open'. Formalized: yes. Let\\[A = \\left\\{ \\sum_{n\\in S}n! : S\\subset \\mathbb{N}\\textrm{ finite}\\right\\}.\\]If $k\\geq 2$, then does $A$ contain only finitely many $k$th powers? Does it contain only finitely many powerful numbers? Current best: This was motivated in part by a problem of Mahler which he discussed with Erd\\H{o}s a few days before his death in 1988: if $k\\geq 5$ and\\[A_k= \\left\\{ \\sum_{n\\in S}k^n : S\\subset \\mathbb{N}\\textrm{ finite}\\right\\}\\]then does $A_k$ contain only finitely many squares? Mahler showed that there are infinitely many squares in $A_k$ for $k\\leq 4$, and found only one square for $k\\geq 5$, namely\\[1+7+7^2+7^3=400.\\]Brindza and Erd\\H{o}s \\cite{BrEr91} proved that, for any $r$, if $n_1!+\\cdots+n_r!$ is powerful then $n_1\\ll_r 1$. Prize: no. OEIS: A025494, A051761, A115645. Tags: factorials, number theory.","id":"vf_d51ac07048efcae6","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/1108.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_54d3d03923222b0a","source_root":"sha256:540d4967071425f77c693e61f62053208b07d67667490dcb9eeef62ec3f1d316","target":"erdos:1108","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Materialized typed link between accepted findings.","inferred":true,"relation":"synthesized_from","source":"vf_54d3d03923222b0a","source_root":"sha256:540d4967071425f77c693e61f62053208b07d67667490dcb9eeef62ec3f1d316","target":"vf_d51ac07048efc